<Layout 
  title="Policy and Legislation"
  description="Understand the policy and legislation behind the UK Armed Forces Compensation Scheme, including recent changes and international treaties.">
  <div class="container my-5">
    <h1 class="display-4 mb-4">Policy and Legislation</h1>
    <div class="row g-4">
      <div class="col-lg-8">
        <p class="lead">The Armed Forces Compensation Scheme (AFCS) is underpinned by robust policy and legislation to ensure fair and consistent support for service personnel and veterans. This page provides an overview of the key policies and legislative framework governing the AFCS.</p>
        
        <h2 class="h3 mt-4">Legislative Framework</h2>
        <p>The AFCS is established under the Armed Forces (Pensions and Compensation) Act 2004 and is governed by The Armed Forces and Reserve Forces (Compensation Scheme) Order 2011. This legislation sets out the rules for eligibility, types of compensation, and the claims process.</p>
        
        <h2 class="h3 mt-4">Recent Changes</h2>
        <p>The AFCS is regularly reviewed to ensure it meets the needs of service personnel and veterans. Recent changes have included:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Increased lump sum payments for certain injuries</li>
          <li>Extended time limits for making claims in specific circumstances</li>
          <li>Enhanced support for mental health conditions</li>
        </ul>
        
        <h2 class="h3 mt-4">International Treaties</h2>
        <p>The UK is a signatory to several international treaties that influence the AFCS, including:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>The Armed Forces Covenant</li>
          <li>NATO Status of Forces Agreement</li>
          <li>Various bilateral agreements with allied nations</li>
        </ul>
        
        <h2 class="h3 mt-4">Government Policies</h2>
        <p>The AFCS is part of the broader government policy to support the Armed Forces community. This includes:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>The Armed Forces Covenant</li>
          <li>Veterans' Strategy</li>
          <li>Defence People Mental Health and Wellbeing Strategy</li>
        </ul>
        
        <p>For more detailed information on specific aspects of AFCS policy and legislation, please visit the pages linked in the sidebar.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="col-lg-4">
        <div class="card bg-light mb-4">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h3 class="h5">Quick Links</h3>
            <ul class="list-unstyled">
              <li><a href="/policy/legislation" class="text-decoration-none">Legislation Details</a></li>
              <li><a href="/policy/recent-changes" class="text-decoration-none">Recent Policy Changes</a></li>
              <li><a href="/policy/international-agreements" class="text-decoration-none">International Agreements</a></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="card mb-4">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h3 class="h5">Stay Informed</h3>
            <p>Sign up for our newsletter to receive updates on AFCS policy changes and legislative developments.</p>
            <a href="/newsletter-signup" class="btn btn-primary">Subscribe</a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>
